BREAK

We will continue to add sample images after finding good Loras so that we can copy and use EXIF in the sample post.

Precautions (Be sure to observe this)

  1. Models may not be traded or sold. Because this is free. .

  2. Models are not available for online paid services. (Free service available)

  3. In using the model, all responsibility lies with the user.

How to high quality

  1. You can output an image like the sample by using an extension to increase the quality. (All sample images were used with the extensions below)

  • 1. Hires.fix -> SwinIR_4x or R-ESRGAN 4x+ Anime6B

  • 2. Dynamic Thresholding (CFG Scale Fix)

  • 3. Detection Detailer (must use)

  • 4. SD upscaler or https://oo.pe/https://www.upscayl.org/

1.Hires.fix ( built-in ) SwinIR (I voted)

2. Dynamic Thresholding

https://github.com/mcmonkeyprojects/sd-dynamic-thresholding.git

3.Detection Detailer

https://github.com/Bing-su/dddetailer.git

Questions that do not use the above four cannot be answered. Please note that images printed without using the four extensions may not look good.

TIP

In order to keep token 75, do not insert resolution, detail, or quality tokens. Since extension add-ons such as DD or DT handle it anyway, there is no need to insert tokens like the ones below.

bad prompt (do not use)

official art, unity 8k wallpaper, ultra detailed, ultra high res, 8k uhd, film grain, delicate, RAW, light particles, detailed skin texture, detailed armor texture, detailed face, intricate details, ultra detailed,

Reality Emphasis Prompt Excludes Detail Emphasis Prompt.

The sample images are created with random prompts and are only examples of what these images can be generated for. Therefore, images and prompts may not match.

items.description:
Low-rank adaptation for Erasing COncepts from diffusion models.

target: "nose" 
positive: "nose"
action: "erase"

When used with positive numbers, it reduces the size of the nostrils and improves an upturned nose. It will be a posture that pulls the chin slightly.

Use negative numbers if you want to see more detail in the nostrils.

It can also be used to make a Otokonoko's face more androgynous, but if the value is too large, it will become feminine.

items.name: Modern Vision
items.description:
This is kinda an experimental merge with my vibe. It is intended for fashion shoots, film and artistic photography

Explore the generation data under the photo in this post. This will give you a clue on how to use this model and what it is intended for

May conflict with other loras, as it already contains my lora in it! You can try to lower the weight of lora (<7) and CFG scale (5.5)

V1 Included model themes down below. You can use the trigger words below in the prompt:

fashion - modern fashion shoots, including creative ones

film grain - cosy film photography

like a painting - photographs in the style of Renaissance paintings, with a touch of romanticism and femininity. You can add clouds, muted colors, flowers to the prompt

eboy - fashionable guys in black clothes and lots of jewelry, idols

couple of lovers - lovestory cosy photoshoots, especially film photography

psychedelic - can give interesting and creative results in the style of photobashes and photo collages

flowers - photographs with people and flowers

makeup - mostly portrait shots, more modern creative makeup

bodyart and statue - can be mixed to get fantasy characters on the verge of realism

There may be a bias towards an asian type of face.

V1 is not for drawings, nsfw, anime, non-human, landscape prompts. V2 works better but is not specified for these topics

V1 Based on Realistic Vision, V2 - including ChillOutMix model

Not for commercial purposes

Tips:

  • 22-30 sampling steps (more detailed composition - more steps)

  • Samplers: DPM++ 2M Karras, DPM++ SDE Karras

  • CFG scale: 5,5(!)-7

  • VAE: vae-ft-mse-840000-ema-pruned for some generations, but not necessary

  • Resolution: 512x768(!) + hires fix using 4x_Struzan or 8x_NMKD-Superscale_150000_G upscaler, ~0.4 Denoising strength, 10-15 Hires steps. Or upscale it in img2img

  • I use Adetailer extension for face and hands, but some generation can be fixed just using Hires fix

items.name: Shigure Kai San (Kancolle)
items.description:
An experimental character LoRA of Sasebo no Shigure from Kantai Collection.

Info

Training with 101 images
Followed the manual form [ [Guide] Make your own Loras, easy and free ],
You can access to this guide in Suggested Resources section.

Recommended set up

Sampler: Euler a, DPM family series
Sampling steps: 20 or 25+
CFG Scale: 7
CLIP Skip: 2
*Do not use [restore face] on anime character!*

This LoRa Weighting: [1 - 0.9], (1 - 0.65)

Baking Step:
0. Drafting (512 x 512 res to find your desired sketch)
1. Hires fix (txt2img: 768 x 768, 768 x 512, 512 x 768, or above res)
2. inpaint (img2img: refine some unwanted effect, [Euler a] with 50+ step)
3. Upscaling (img2img: res*2 with [ControlNet Tile] & Ultimate SD upscale)

Upscaler for [Step 1 - 3]: [R-ESRGAN 4x+ Anime6B, 4x-AnimeSharp, 4x-UltraSharp]
I always skip Step 0, 2 :P

Basic prompts

ShigureKaiSanKC, (sleeveless) shirt, (black and white) two-tone shirt, (black) pleated skirt, (black) thighhighs, (red) necktie, (white) belt, (black) fingerless gloves, (red) hand ribbon

Special outfits

ShigureKaiSanCasualKC, (long sleeves), hat, (white) beret, (white) shirt, (white) dress, (black) jacket, (red) necktie

Some additional tags that you may use for reference

-hair over shoulder, hair ornament, hair between eyes, blue eyes

items.name: Peter Doig Style
items.description:
Peter Doig is a contemporary Scottish-born artist known for his evocative and atmospheric paintings. Born in 1959, Doig has become one of the most respected and influential artists of his generation.

Doig's paintings often depict landscapes, both real and imagined, with a dreamlike quality. His works are characterized by their rich colors, layered brushwork, and a sense of mystery and introspection. He explores themes of memory, identity, and the relationship between humans and nature.

One of Doig's signature techniques is his use of loose brushstrokes and thick layers of paint, creating a textured surface that adds depth and a sense of movement to his compositions. His paintings often convey a sense of isolation, with figures placed within vast and immersive landscapes.

While Doig's works have been associated with various art movements, such as Neo-Romanticism and Magic Realism, his style defies strict categorization. He draws inspiration from diverse sources, including photographs, films, and personal memories, which he translates onto the canvas with his unique artistic vision.

Doig's paintings have a haunting and ethereal quality that invites viewers to engage with their own emotions and interpretations. His ability to capture a sense of time and place, while leaving room for imagination, has garnered him international acclaim.

Peter Doig's contributions to contemporary art have solidified his position as one of the most important painters of his generation. His distinctive style, rooted in both observation and imagination, continues to captivate audiences and provoke contemplation about the nature of perception and the power of the painted image.

items.name: Peter Paul Rubens Style
items.description:
Peter Paul Rubens was a Flemish Baroque painter who lived from 1577 to 1640. He is regarded as one of the most influential artists of his time and one of the foremost painters in European history.

Rubens' art is known for its dynamic compositions, dramatic use of light and shadow, and rich, sensual depictions of the human form. He was a master of color and movement, combining classical influences with his own innovative techniques to create artworks that were both powerful and visually stunning.

His subjects ranged from religious and mythological scenes to portraits and landscapes. Rubens' ability to capture the human figure in various poses and expressions, as well as his skillful rendering of texture and detail, contributed to the lifelike quality of his paintings.

items.name: Philippe Druillet Style
items.description:
Philippe Druillet is a French artist and writer known for his influential contributions to the realms of comics and graphic novels. Born in 1944, Druillet emerged as a prominent figure in the 1970s, and his distinctive artistic style left a lasting impact on the genre of science fiction and fantasy art.

Druillet's artwork is characterized by its dark, surreal, and intricate nature. He often depicted futuristic and dystopian worlds, combining elements of science fiction, fantasy, and cosmic imagery. His compositions are highly detailed, filled with intricate line work, and characterized by bold use of color and dramatic lighting.

One of his most renowned works is the series "Lone Sloane," which follows the adventures of the titular character in a universe filled with intricate narratives, strange creatures, and mystical landscapes. Druillet's storytelling is often non-linear and experimental, challenging traditional narrative structures and immersing readers in a surreal and dreamlike experience.

His artistic style has been described as baroque and visionary, with a strong emphasis on conveying emotions and atmosphere. Druillet's works often explore themes of power, transformation, and the fragility of the human condition.

Beyond his graphic novels, Druillet has also made significant contributions to the field of illustration and design. He has created album covers, movie posters, and concept art, further showcasing his talent and versatility as an artist.

Philippe Druillet's unique artistic vision and his contributions to the world of comics and graphic novels have left an indelible mark. His surreal and imaginative worlds continue to inspire artists and captivate audiences, solidifying his place as a visionary figure in the realm of science fiction and fantasy art.

items.name: Pierre Auguste Renoir Style
items.description:
Pierre-Auguste Renoir was a French artist who lived from 1841 to 1919 and is considered one of the leading figures of Impressionism. Known for his mastery of color, light, and capturing the beauty of everyday life, Renoir's works are celebrated for their charm and vibrancy.

Renoir's style evolved over the course of his career. In his early years, he embraced the techniques of the Realist movement, but later transitioned to Impressionism, adopting a looser brushwork and a focus on capturing the transient effects of light and color.

His subjects often included landscapes, portraits, and scenes of people engaged in leisurely activities. Renoir had a special talent for capturing the fleeting moments and natural grace of his subjects, infusing his paintings with a sense of joy and vitality.

Renoir's approach to color was characterized by his use of vibrant hues and delicate tonal transitions. He employed a technique known as "broken color," applying small strokes of pure color side by side to create luminous effects and capture the impression of light reflecting off surfaces.

In addition to his contributions to painting, Renoir also embraced sculpture, experimenting with three-dimensional forms and exploring the tactile qualities of the medium.

Despite facing physical challenges later in life due to arthritis, Renoir continued to paint with the aid of an easel attached to his wheelchair. His determination to create art until the end of his life is a testament to his passion and dedication to his craft.

Pierre-Auguste Renoir's legacy is profound, and his works continue to be celebrated for their beauty and ability to capture the essence of the Impressionist movement. His contributions to the art world, particularly in the realm of color and light, have left an indelible mark on the history of art.

items.name: Pierre Bonnard Style
items.description:
Pierre Bonnard was a French painter and printmaker who lived from 1867 to 1947. He was a prominent figure in the Post-Impressionist and Nabis movements and is known for his intimate and atmospheric paintings.

Bonnard's art is characterized by his unique approach to color and composition. He often depicted scenes from everyday life, including domestic interiors, landscapes, and still lifes. His paintings have a sense of intimacy and quietude, capturing ordinary moments with a heightened sense of color and light.

One of Bonnard's distinctive techniques was his use of vibrant and unconventional color combinations. He employed rich, vibrant hues, often using non-naturalistic colors to evoke a certain mood or emotion. Bonnard's color harmonies created a sense of depth and atmosphere, imbuing his works with a sense of warmth and luminosity.

His compositions were often cropped and unconventional, with figures and objects placed in unexpected positions, giving his works a sense of spontaneity and dynamism. Bonnard had a keen eye for capturing the play of light and shadow, as well as the interplay between interior and exterior spaces.

Bonnard's paintings also showcased his interest in the decorative arts, with his use of patterns, textiles, and intricate details. He was influenced by Japanese prints and incorporated elements of Japonism into his art.

Throughout his career, Bonnard explored various mediums, including painting, printmaking, and photography. His experimentation with different techniques allowed him to continually innovate and push the boundaries of his art.

Pierre Bonnard's art continues to captivate viewers with its vibrant colors, poetic compositions, and intimate glimpses into everyday life. His unique approach to color and composition, as well as his ability to convey emotion through his paintings, have secured his place as one of the significant figures in the history of modern art.

items.name: Pieter Claesz Style
items.description:
Pieter Claesz was a Dutch Golden Age painter who lived from 1597 to 1660. He was known for his still life paintings, particularly those featuring sumptuous displays of food and table settings.

Claesz's still life compositions were highly detailed and meticulously executed. He had a remarkable ability to capture the textures and surfaces of objects, rendering them with precision and lifelike quality. His paintings often depicted arrangements of fruits, meats, cheeses, and various tableware, creating scenes of abundance and opulence.

One of his notable contributions to the still life genre was his mastery of light and shadow. Claesz employed a technique known as chiaroscuro, where he contrasted areas of light and dark to create a sense of depth and three-dimensionality. The interplay of light and shadow added a sense of drama and realism to his paintings.

Claesz's choice of subject matter and meticulous attention to detail reflected the growing interest in material possessions and luxury goods during the Dutch Golden Age. His paintings conveyed messages of wealth, abundance, and the transient nature of earthly pleasures.

In addition to his still life paintings, Claesz also painted vanitas scenes, which symbolically represented the transience of life and the inevitability of death. These paintings often featured objects such as skulls, hourglasses, and extinguished candles, serving as reminders of the fleeting nature of earthly existence.

Pieter Claesz's contribution to the still life genre and his technical skill in capturing the beauty of objects and the play of light have made him one of the renowned painters of the Dutch Golden Age. His works continue to be admired for their exquisite detail, masterful technique, and exploration of the themes of materialism and mortality.

Staprans' paintings are characterized by their bold, vibrant colors and simplified, abstracted forms. He often depicts everyday objects, such as chairs, tables, and fruits, as well as landscapes and cityscapes. His compositions have a sense of order and balance, and he pays careful attention to the interplay of light and shadow.

One of the notable aspects of Staprans' art is his use of color. He employs a heightened color palette, with vivid hues that are often unexpected yet harmonious. His colors create a sense of energy and vibrancy, infusing his paintings with a dynamic quality.

Staprans' still lifes and landscapes evoke a sense of nostalgia and familiarity. They often depict scenes from his native Latvia or his adopted home of California, capturing the essence of these places with a distinct personal perspective.

In addition to his subject matter, Staprans' brushwork is another defining element of his art. He uses bold, confident brushstrokes that give his paintings a textured and expressive quality. His application of paint varies from thin and transparent to thick and impasto, adding depth and dimension to his compositions.

Raimonds Staprans' unique style, characterized by his use of vibrant colors, simplified forms, and expressive brushwork, sets him apart as a distinctive voice in contemporary painting. Now, that's what I have done with this model and I will keep working on it.

I have trained the model on a large amount of women of any kind, using the waifu diffusion tagger, and by doing this the model captured the single features of each woman and mixed them together to get info for the celebrities that the encoder knows about but the unet is not trained on.

Currently the model has low capability on NSFW stuff, but I will try to make it work next, until then you can have some acceptable depictions of celebrities, I very well know these photos aren't perfect but it is a huge step forward on the basic model.

Ah, since it is not overfitting, it should be able to deal with other concepts, try yourself and, since it was smartly merged with Illuminutty you can try with their embeddings...

items.name: SDXL 0.9 Iterative Workflow
items.description:
Intro

This workflow and supporting custom node will support iterating over the SDXL 0.9 Base Model + Refiner Model combo, as well as perform a Hires. Fix (approximation) to improve on the quality of the generation. This is more of an experimentation workflow than one that will produce amazing, ultrarealistic images. It allows you to run essentially unlimited number of iterations on an image.

What does it do?

One of the common methods being tested for SDXL 0.9 image generation is running the base model for ~80% of the total steps, and then running the refiner model for the remaining ~20% of the total steps. This process can then be repeated multiple times to adjust the image. The problem is that currently this would require you to duplicate the nodes for every iteration of this. To clean this up, I created an iterative KSampler that supports multiple models (ie. Base & Refiner) as well as separate positive and negative prompt inputs for each. This node technically isn't limited to just SDXL, but was built with that in mind.

Note: I have not found the "best" values for iterations, denoising strength, samplers, base model %, etc. Feel free to try changing these values and seeing what effect it has!

How to install it?

  1. Download the workflow zip file

  2. Extract the zip file

  3. Move the extracted iterative node python file to your custom_nodes folder: ComfyUI/custom_nodes/

  4. Launch (or relaunch) ComfyUI

  5. Load the workflow by pressing the Load button and selecting the extracted workflow json file

  6. Select Queue Prompt to generate an image

Quality of life add-ons

I highly suggest downloading this ComfyUI Manger extension as well for ComfyUI as it will make downloading other extensions MUCH easier moving forwards. In addition to that, if there are any dependencies that you do not already have fulfilled, it can auto-download those for you.

Download URL: https://civitai.com/models/71980/comfyui-manager

He introduced the concept of integrating illustrations and text on the same page, creating a seamless narrative flow. His use of dynamic compositions and imaginative storytelling revolutionized children's book illustration.

Caldecott's illustrations were also renowned for their use of color and texture. He employed watercolors, ink, and other media to bring his characters and scenes to life, creating a sense of depth and atmosphere.

In recognition of his significant contributions to children's literature, the Caldecott Medal was established in his honor. It is awarded annually to the most distinguished illustrated children's book published in the United States.

Randolph Caldecott's influence on the field of children's book illustration is profound. His innovative approach to storytelling and his captivating illustrations continue to inspire and delight readers of all ages. His legacy as a pioneering illustrator has left an enduring impact on the world of children's literature.

items.name: Ray Caesar Style
items.description:
Ray Caesar is a Canadian artist known for his digital artworks that blend elements of surrealism, fantasy, and portraiture. Born in 1958, Caesar creates visually captivating and emotionally evocative pieces that invite viewers into dreamlike worlds.

Caesar's art is primarily created using digital techniques, combining digital painting, 3D modeling, and photo manipulation. His works often feature delicate, porcelain-like figures, often young girls or women, set against ornate and fantastical backdrops. These figures possess a unique mix of fragility and strength, conveying complex emotions and narratives.

The themes explored in Caesar's art often revolve around human identity, vulnerability, and the intersection of reality and fantasy. His pieces have a dreamlike quality, blurring the lines between the conscious and the unconscious, and inviting viewers to delve into the realms of the imagination.

In terms of style, Caesar's art is highly detailed and meticulously crafted. The intricate details, soft color palettes, and seamless blending of elements give his works a sense of otherworldly beauty. His use of symbolism and allegory adds depth and layers of meaning to his art, allowing viewers to interpret and connect with the narratives presented.

Throughout his career, Caesar has received international recognition and has exhibited his artworks in galleries around the world. His unique blend of digital artistry, surrealism, and emotional storytelling has earned him a dedicated following and solidified his place as a notable figure in contemporary art.

Ray Caesar's art invites viewers to explore the realms of imagination, emotion, and human identity. His mesmerizing and thought-provoking artworks continue to captivate and intrigue, inviting us to contemplate the complexities of the human experience in surreal and enchanting ways.

items.name: Remedios Varo Style
items.description:
Remedios Varo (1908-1963) was a Spanish-Mexican surrealist painter known for her enigmatic and dreamlike artworks. Born in Spain, she later settled in Mexico and became associated with the Surrealist movement.

Varo's paintings are characterized by their meticulous detail, symbolic imagery, and surreal narratives. Her works often depict fantastical worlds inhabited by mysterious and magical beings. Influenced by alchemy, mysticism, and esoteric philosophies, Varo's art explores themes of transformation, identity, and the human condition.

Her compositions are filled with intricate and symbolic elements, creating a sense of mystery and intrigue. She employed a wide range of techniques, including precise brushwork, delicate textures, and luminous colors, to bring her imaginative visions to life.

Varo's works often feature female protagonists, strong and independent women who navigate mysterious realms and encounter fantastical situations. Through her art, she explored the complexities of femininity, spirituality, and the human psyche.

Despite facing personal and professional challenges during her lifetime, Varo's unique style and visionary approach to painting have earned her recognition and admiration. Her artworks continue to captivate audiences with their poetic and introspective qualities, inviting viewers to embark on a journey of self-discovery and contemplation.

Remedios Varo's contributions to surrealism and her ability to create evocative and thought-provoking artworks have solidified her status as a notable figure in 20th-century art. Her imaginative and visionary approach continues to inspire artists and enthusiasts alike, leaving a lasting legacy in the world of surrealist painting.

items.name: Richard Corben Style
items.description:
Richard Corben (1940-2020) was an American artist and illustrator known for his contributions to the fields of comics, illustration, and fantasy art. He was particularly renowned for his work in the horror and science fiction genres.

Corben's distinctive style was characterized by its detailed linework, bold colors, and muscular, exaggerated figures. He had a talent for creating visually striking and often macabre imagery, capturing the dark and fantastical elements of the stories he illustrated.

Corben gained prominence in the underground comix scene of the 1970s, where he created his own original stories and characters. His notable works include "Den," a science fiction/fantasy series, and "Rip in Time," a series featuring a time-traveling adventurer.

Throughout his career, Corben collaborated with various writers and publishers, including Marvel Comics and Heavy Metal magazine. He provided illustrations for numerous comic book series, including "Hellboy," "Swamp Thing," and "Creepy."

One of Corben's notable contributions to the medium was his use of airbrushing techniques, which added a distinct level of texture and depth to his artwork. His illustrations often showcased intricate details and a strong sense of atmosphere, enhancing the overall impact of the narratives he worked on.

Corben's work has received critical acclaim and earned him numerous awards, including the Eisner Award and the Spectrum Grand Master Award. His artistry and storytelling skills continue to inspire and influence artists working in the realms of comics, illustration, and fantasy art.

Richard Corben's contributions to the fields of comics and fantasy art have left a lasting impact. His unique visual style and ability to create vivid and atmospheric imagery have made him a highly respected figure in the industry. Even after his passing, his legacy as a master of the macabre and fantastical lives on through his influential body of work.
